	HIGH ground        
	Greenpeace activists climbed halfway up the Colosseum in Rome to press for a climate deal at Copenhagen. Eight people used ropes and their hands to reach the top of the second tier of the monuments four tiers        
	MISSING link        
	UN climate talks have neglected a food crisis, including measures which can both curb climate change and boost food production, the head of the UNs Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO) said. Historically the discussion centred on the industrial aspects of climate change, Jacques Diouf said, adding that farming  along with the deforestation it drives  accounts for nearly 31 per cent of emissions. FAO says cutting stocking rates and applying organic materials to the land can sequester CO2 in the soil equivalent to 10 per cent of global emissions, and help slow warming. Some scientists say greenhouse gas emissions from raising cattle may account for half the global emission, prompting calls to eat less meat        
